statements.1:
The Goal

The goal of the game is to create a maze layout to hinder a group of heroes trying to rob the treasures and escape.
The game is based on Code Keeper - The Hero multiplayer game, where you take the role of hero and try to survive the maze.

  Rules

This is the procedural content generation task. The architect is given a partially filled maze and has to place a specified number of entities to make it hard for the heroes.

Base game

All game mechanics are the same as in Code Keeper - The Hero. This includes the types of entities and how their work, as well as rules for the monsters and the heroes. The only difference is that in this game the heroes are controlled by some predefined bots.

Placing entities

The base maze is given as a list of already placed entities (they all occupy different maze cells). These entities cannot be modified by the architect.
For each possible entity type (except the hero starting position) the architect is given number of entities of that type to place on the map (between 0 and 50).
Given this data, the architect has a single turn to provide a list of entity placements (in a form of x y type triplets). All required entity types in right quantities have to be placed. Also, each cell can contain at most one entity.

Scoring

The goal of the architect is to minimize the score of the heroes. Each test has four hero agents assigned to run the maze created by the architect. The final score of the architect is the sum of heroes scores, and the lower the score, the higher the architect ranking.
However, to make the challenge fairer, the architect has to restrain his powers and make sure that the mazes he creates are passable. Thus, at least one of the heroes needs to successfully escape the maze (step into an exit cell) to make the architect pass the test. If all heroes are destroyed by the monsters or fail to reach the exit within their turn limit (150) the test failes for the architect regardless of the score achieved.

Acknowledgments

This contribution was developed for the Artificial Intelligence for Games, 2021 edition course, University of Wrocaw, 2021.

Authored by Jakub Kowalski (@aCat).

Additional thanks to: @radekmie, @Gabbek.



  Game Input

Initial input
First line: 12 space-separated integers. The i-th integer contains the number of entities of type i the architect has to place in the maze. The types of entities are listed below (note that there will never be an option to place hero, i.e. entity of type 12).
Next line: An integer existingEntities for the number of the entities already exiting in the maze.
Next existingEntities lines: 3 space-separated integers to describe each entity:
  • ex: x position of the entity.
  • ey: y position of the entity.
  • etype: the type of the entity:
    • 0: exit.
    • 1: obstacle.
    • 2: treasure.
    • 3: potion.
    • 4: charge for hammer.
    • 5: charge for scythe.
    • 6: charge for bow.
    • 7: box.
    • 8: skeleton.
    • 9: gargoyle.
    • 10: orc.
    • 11: vampire.
    • 12: hero.
Output
One line for each entity to place:
  • x y etype to place entity of type etype at a given cell with coordinates x, y.
Constraints
Response time 25s
